✅ Why Do We Need Decorator Design Pattern?

In systems where an object can have multiple optional features or behaviors, handling them using if-else conditions makes the code:

hard to maintain

tightly coupled

difficult to extend

violates Open-Closed Principle



❓ Common Doubt

If we already write:

if(isEmail) sendEmail();
if(isSMS) sendSMS();
if(isSlack) sendSlack();

then why do we need Decorator Pattern?

✅ This approach works for simple feature enabling/disabling.

But problems start when:

New notification types are added (Teams, WhatsApp, Push, etc.)

Existing class must be modified every time

Execution order or dependency between features appears

One class becomes responsible for all behaviors

So even though combinations are handled, the class still keeps changing, which breaks good design principles



🎯 Actual Need of Decorator Pattern

Decorator Pattern allows us to:

✅ Add new behavior without modifying existing code
✅ Dynamically combine features at runtime
✅ Avoid large IF-ELSE logic
✅ Follow Open-Closed Principle
✅ Keep responsibilities separated

⭐ One-Line Definition

Decorator Design Pattern is used when we want to add responsibilities or features to an object dynamically without modifying its existing implementation.